{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782387528247,"sessionID":"ses_1016ce029ffemCaBB5i2jTaXCt","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_nmfgNDCcfsllU8bJ8tHf8cVZ","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\Kotlin2Cangjie\\docs\\android-kotlin-to-cangjie-agent-protocol.md","limit":260},"output":"<path>D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\Kotlin2Cangjie\\docs\\android-kotlin-to-cangjie-agent-protocol.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Android Kotlin to HarmonyOS Cangjie Agent Protocol\n2: \n3: This protocol is the stable instruction source for `opencode-cj` sessions in the Android Kotlin to HarmonyOS Cangjie workflow. Human operators and orchestration scripts may reference this file from generated prompts.\n4: \n5: ## 1. Role\n6: \n7: You are the translation agent for an Android Kotlin app to HarmonyOS Cangjie app migration.\n8: \n9: You perform the actual target-project source translation and target-project source fixes. You preserve the source app's user-visible behavior while adapting implementation, resources, data flow, state management, and build configuration to HarmonyOS Cangjie patterns.\n10: \n11: ## 2. Authority Boundaries\n12: \n13: - You may modify files under `<target-project>/`.\n14: - You may create or update `plan.md` and strict `plan.json` during planning.\n15: - Do not modify `<source-project>/`.\n16: - Do not modify `translation-inputs/` except when a prompt explicitly asks you to write a small deferred note there.\n17: - Do not modify `translation-records/`.\n18: - Do not modify workflow scripts, analyzer code, build-gate scripts, or this protocol unless the user explicitly asks for toolchain work.\n19: - Do not replace the orchestration flow with a separate translator, analyzer, or build system.\n20: - Do not assume app-specific names from previous migrations.\n21: \n22: ## 3. Required Inputs\n23: \n24: Read the relevant files before making decisions:\n25: \n26: - `task-planning.md`\n27: - `plan.md`\n28: - `plan.json`\n29: - `translation-inputs/preflight-report.md`\n30: - `translation-inputs/sdk-report.json`\n31: - `translation-inputs/skills-report.md`\n32: - `translation-inputs/plan-seed.md` and `translation-inputs/plan-seed.json` when present\n33: - `translation-inputs/source-feature-survey.md`\n34: - `translation-inputs/resource-coverage-report.md`\n35: - `translation-inputs/coverage-gap-report.md`\n36: - `translation-inputs/kotlin-analysis/gradle-model.json`\n37: - `translation-inputs/kotlin-analysis/analysis.json`\n38: - `translation-inputs/kotlin-analysis/locations.json`\n39: - `translation-inputs/kotlin-analysis/planning-note.md`\n40: - `translation-inputs/android-analysis/manifest-summary.json`\n41: - `translation-inputs/android-analysis/resource-map.json`\n42: - `translation-inputs/android-analysis/screen-map.json`\n43: - `translation-inputs/android-analysis/view-bindings.json`\n44: - `translation-inputs/android-analysis/layout-tree.json`\n45: - `translation-inputs/android-analysis/drawable-semantics.json`\n46: - `translation-inputs/android-analysis/adapter-map.json`\n47: - `translation-inputs/android-analysis/behavior-spec.md`\n48: - `X2Cangjie/docs/harmonyos-cangjie-translation-checklist.md`\n49: - The current phase's `build-report.md`, if fixing a build blocker.\n50: - The current phase's `opencode-build-blocker-prompt.txt`, if fixing a build blocker.\n51: \n52: If an input is missing, continue only when the missing input is not essential for the requested step. Report the gap.\n53: \n54: `translation-inputs/kotlin-analysis/planning-note.md` may report multiple Kotlin or Java source roots. Treat that as the normal multi-module case and use the combined `analysis.json` plus source files as the structural reference for all modules.\n55: \n56: If multi-module analysis failed before translation planning because the analyzer protocol probe failed, do not work around it in the target project. Ask the operator to rebuild the analyzer instead of proceeding from partial static inputs.\n57: \n58: ## 3.1 Static Analysis Scope\n59: \n60: Treat `translation-inputs/` as structured planning evidence and indexes, not as a complete source of truth. Do not assume a source feature is absent only because it is missing from generated analysis.\n61: \n62: Use `source-feature-survey.md`, `resource-coverage-report.md`, and `coverage-gap-report.md` as a coverage baseline. Their purpose is to reduce functional gaps and unexplained code-scale gaps. Do not mechanically match source LoC; instead, map current-phase critical/high source files, resources, tests, and platform integrations to target implementation, supplemental tests, or explicit deferred items with source evidence and reason.\n63: \n64: For current-phase decisions:\n65: \n66: - Use structured inputs first to locate relevant source screens, composables, resources, data paths, settings/preferences, callbacks, navigation, persistence, Compose state, ViewModel/repository flow, and state-refresh behavior.\n67: - If behavior, resources, bindings, navigation, persistence, or state refresh semantics are unclear, inspect the minimal relevant source project files.\n68: - If source code contradicts or supplements generated analysis, follow the source code.\n69: - Report the analysis gap so later phases do not inherit a false assumption.\n70: \n71: ## 3.2 Kotlin-Specific Behavior Evidence\n72: \n73: When the source app uses Jetpack Compose, inspect composables, remembered state, state hoisting, callbacks, navigation routes, LazyColumn/LazyRow contents, dialogs, bottom bars, and event handlers before planning target files.\n74: \n75: When the source app uses XML/ViewBinding, inspect Activity/Fragment lifecycle flow, adapters, RecyclerView/ListView refresh behavior, click listeners, validation, and navigation before planning target files.\n76: \n77: When the source app uses ViewModel, StateFlow, LiveData, coroutine, repository, Room, Retrofit, Firebase, DataStore, or SharedPreferences, preserve the user-visible observable behavior even if the translated implementation uses local HarmonyOS-compatible abstractions.\n78: \n79: ## 4. Planning Session Requirements\n80: \n81: In a planning session, generate or update:\n82: \n83: - `plan.md`\n84: - `plan.json`\n85: \n86: `plan.md` must define the migration phases, phase goals, phase dependencies, build gates, review points, deferred items, and behavior risks.\n87: \n88: `plan.json` must be strict JSON and cover:\n89: \n90: - `files`: target files, source references, top-level definitions, and translation guidelines.\n91: - `assets`: strings, images, colors, layouts, styles, vectors, animations, menus, and resource adaptation rules.\n92: - `dependencies`: third-party dependencies and their HarmonyOS Cangjie replacement strategy.\n93: - `tests`: existing source tests to migrate, generated tests for uncovered core behavior, supplemental tests for shallow source coverage, and test commands or deferred validation.\n94: - `phases`: canonical phase identifiers, target scope, required inputs, expected files, implementation groups, and gate criteria.\n95: - `deferred`: known incomplete items, reason, owner phase, and validation needed.\n96: \n97: Planning must explicitly map:\n98: \n99: - `plan-seed` source units, callable function/composable/event-handler contracts, UI contracts, data contracts, resource contracts, platform capability contracts, structure risks, and analysis gaps to phases and implementation groups.\n100: - Kotlin classes, Android Activities, Fragments, ViewModels, repositories, Compose composables, XML/ViewBinding screens, adapters, listeners, callbacks, StateFlow/LiveData observers, and coroutine-driven side effects.\n101: - Android resources and layouts to HarmonyOS resources and ArkUI builders.\n102: - Persistence, backend SDKs, local storage, network APIs, and CRUD/data-flow behavior.\n103: - UI state, observable data, navigation, validation, error messages, and refresh semantics.\n104: - Source tests and project-specific verification assets to target tests or target-side validation cases.\n105: \n106: Each implementation group in `plan.json` should include stable `groupId`, `title`, `groupType`, `priority`, `sourcePaths`, source function/composable or callable contract references when available, `featureIds`, `resourceInputs`, `platformCapabilityIds`, UI/data contract references or hints, `expectedTargetDomains`, `requiredBehaviors`, `riskHints`, and `acceptanceEvidence`. Treat `plan-seed` as planning evidence, not a complete source of truth; inspect source files when behavior is unclear or when source code contradicts static analysis, and record `analysisGaps` or `sourceOverrides` instead of silently dropping behavior.\n107: \n108: Do not implement the migration during a planning-only session unless the human prompt explicitly authorizes it.\n109: \n110: ## 5. Build Phase Rules\n111: \n112: For every phase:\n113: \n114: - Re-read `task-planning.md`, `plan.md`, and `plan.json`.\n115: - Read the structured analysis inputs relevant to this phase.\n116: - Work only on the current phase's scope unless a small prerequisite fix is required.\n117: - Keep source-file structure understandable; do not collapse the app into one large file.\n118: - Prefer HarmonyOS Cangjie idioms and the checklist over Android or ArkTS assumptions.\n119: - Do not leave direct Android SDK, Firebase SDK, or unavailable third-party library references in target Cangjie code unless explicitly deferred with a replacement plan.\n120: - Migrate source tests relevant to the current phase. If source tests are absent or too shallow for current phase behavior, add focused target-side tests for translated business, data, state, validation, refresh, Compose state, ViewModel/repository flow, or persistence logic.\n121: - Prefer runnable target-project tests. If a behavior cannot be automated with the available template/SDK in this phase, keep the code testable and record the deferred validation path.\n122: - After edits, review the target project against `plan.md` and `plan.json`.\n123: - If `apply_patch` fails, read back affected files before retrying.\n124: - If a long session is interrupted, inspect the current filesystem state before continuing.\n125: \n126: ## 6. Build Blocker Fix Rules\n127: \n128: When fixing a build blocker:\n129: \n130: - Read `build-report.md`.\n131: - Read `opencode-build-blocker-prompt.txt`.\n132: - Fix the first visible blocker or the smallest coherent blocker class.\n133: - Do not perform unrelated redesigns.\n134: - Do not advance to a new phase.\n135: - Preserve phase intent and existing completed work.\n136: - Do not delete, disable, or weaken migrated/generated tests merely to make the build pass. Fix the implementation or record an explicit deferred test limitation when necessary.\n137: - After fixing, state which blocker was addressed and what still needs a build gate rerun.\n138: \n139: ## 7. Phase-End Checks\n140: \n141: At the end of a phase:\n142: \n143: - Check whether current target files contradict `plan.md` or `plan.json`.\n144: - Check whether the phase introduced files or code not needed by current or later phases.\n145: - Check whether UI state transitions and data refresh paths required by this phase are represented.\n146: - Check whether resources referenced by code exist in the target resource tree.\n147: - Check whether current-phase tests were migrated, generated, supplemented, run when possible, or explicitly deferred.\n148: - Check whether deferred state-machine, data-flow, backend, runtime, or resource gaps are recorded.\n149: \n150: ## 8. Prompt Templates\n151: \n152: ### Planning Session Template\n153: \n154: Use this shape when the orchestration script starts a planning session:\n155: \n156: ```text\n157: Read and follow the agent protocol: <agent-protocol>.\n158: Read and follow task-planning.md: <task-planning>.\n159: This is a planning session only.\n160: Generate or update <plan.md> and <plan.json>.\n161: Use translation-inputs as structured planning evidence.\n162: Do not modify source project files.\n163: Do not modify translation-records or workflow scripts.\n164: Report changed files, commands run, plan coverage, missing inputs, and deferred risks.\n165: ```\n166: \n167: ### Phase Session Template\n168: \n169: Use this shape when the orchestration script starts a phase session:\n170: \n171: ```text\n172: Read and follow the agent protocol: <agent-protocol>.\n173: Read task-planning.md, plan.md, and plan.json before editing.\n174: Start only phase <phase>.\n175: Use relevant translation-inputs and the HarmonyOS Cangjie checklist.\n176: Modify only the target project files needed for this phase.\n177: Do not skip phase-end checks.\n178: Report changed files, commands run, build status if known, plan changes, deferred issues, and next recommended action.\n179: ```\n180: \n181: ### Build Blocker Template\n182: \n183: Use this shape when the orchestration script starts a build-blocker fix session:\n184: \n185: ```text\n186: Read and follow the agent protocol: <agent-protocol>.\n187: Read the build blocker prompt: <opencode-build-blocker-prompt.txt>.\n188: Read the build report before editing.\n189: Fix only the current phase's build blocker or smallest coherent blocker class.\n190: Do not perform unrelated refactors.\n191: Report changed files, commands run, blocker addressed, remaining blockers, deferred issues, and next recommended action.\n192: ```\n193: \n194: ## 9. Required Final Response Format\n195: \n196: End every session with:\n197: \n198: ```text\n199: Changed files:\n200: - <path>: <what changed>\n201: \n202: Commands run:\n203: - <command or \"none\">\n204: \n205: Build result:\n206: - <PASS/FAIL/NOT RUN/UNKNOWN and report path if available>\n207: \n208: Plan changes:\n209: - <plan updates or \"none\">\n210: \n211: Deferred issues:\n212: - <issue, owner phase, validation needed, or \"none\">\n213: \n214: Next recommended action:\n215: - <one concrete next step>\n216: ```\n\n(End of file - total 216 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Android Kotlin to HarmonyOS Cangjie Agent Protocol\n\nThis protocol is the stable instruction source for `opencode-cj` sessions in the Android Kotlin to HarmonyOS Cangjie workflow. Human operators and orchestration scripts may reference this file from generated prompts.\n\n## 1. Role\n\nYou are the translation agent for an Android Kotlin app to HarmonyOS Cangjie app migration.\n\nYou perform the actual target-project source translation and target-project source fixes. You preserve the source app's user-visible behavior while adapting implementation, resources, data flow, state management, and build configuration to HarmonyOS Cangjie patterns.\n\n## 2. Authority Boundaries\n\n- You may modify files under `<target-project>/`.\n- You may create or update `plan.md` and strict `plan.json` during planning.\n- Do not modify `<source-project>/`.\n- Do not modify `translation-inputs/` except when a prompt explicitly asks you to write a small deferred note there.\n- Do not modify `translation-records/`.\n- Do not modify workflow scripts, analyzer code, build-gate scripts, or this protocol unless the user explicitly asks for toolchain work.\n- Do not replace the orchestration flow with a separate translator, analyzer, or build system.\n- Do not assume app-specific names from previous migrations.","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"..\\..\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\Kotlin2Cangjie\\docs\\android-kotlin-to-cangjie-agent-protocol.md","time":{"start":1782387528228,"end":1782387528246}},"id":"prt_efe9351e0001CPOveJO2tyAhXI","sessionID":"ses_1016ce029ffemCaBB5i2jTaXCt","messageID":"msg_efe933ccf001HylW623iKQze4Y"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782387528253,"sessionID":"ses_1016ce029ffemCaBB5i2jTaXCt","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_tGnX5zluW4TQNGw3I6ElSx7D","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\plan.md","limit":260},"output":"<path>D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\plan.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Foodike HarmonyOS Cangjie Migration Plan\n2: \n3: ## Scope\n4: \n5: - Source project: `D:\\Kotlin2Cangjie\\Foodike`\n6: - Target project: `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony`\n7: - Session type: planning only\n8: - Source app shape: single-module Jetpack Compose app with splash-gated startup, Compose navigation, static fixture-backed content, and DataStore-backed login persistence.\n9: \n10: ## Confirmed Source Behavior\n11: \n12: - Startup uses `SplashViewModel` plus Android splash screen keep-on-screen behavior to resolve the first route before showing the app shell.\n13: - Initial route is `onboarding` when login state is false and `home` when login state is true.\n14: - Navigation shell owns the nav controller, a shared list scroll state, a floating cart button, and conditional bottom-bar visibility.\n15: - Onboarding is a three-page pager with next-step progression and final navigation to login.\n16: - Login stores only a boolean logged-in flag. Valid credentials are hard-coded to `abcxyz@gmail.com` and `abcdef`; invalid login emits a snackbar.\n17: - Home loads ads, recommended food cards, restaurant lists, and favourites from repositories. Selecting a restaurant stores the active restaurant in session state before navigating to detail.\n18: - History reads liked restaurants from the same session repository and also stores the selected restaurant before navigating to detail.\n19: - Restaurant detail reads the selected restaurant, derives recommended/non-veg/veg menu sections, toggles section expansion and local liked state, and shows the floating cart button only when the summed local item count is non-zero.\n20: - Cart currently reads repository cart snapshots but keeps bill totals, delivery restaurant, item-note editor, and quantity buttons mostly as local UI behavior with no persistent mutation wiring.\n21: - Profile shows static profile information and toggles the persisted login state on logout before clearing navigation history back to onboarding.\n22: - Real persistence is limited to login state. Restaurant selection, favourites, menu counts, liked state, and cart snapshots are in-memory session state only.\n23: \n24: ## Static Analysis Overrides\n25: \n26: - Generated platform-capability heuristics over-report media library, SAF/file access, runtime permissions, and notification/widget behavior. Source walkthrough evidence shows no actual media picker, external storage, SAF, dangerous permission request, service, receiver, widget, or notification flow in the app.\n27: - `Navigation.kt` contains a duplicated onboarding destination entry. Planning keeps the intended destination set but treats the duplicate as source cleanup noise, not a required user-visible behavior.\n28: - `SearchBar`, `ChipBar`, `MenuItemCard`, `ItemSection`, and some cart/detail interactions are currently local UI state only. They still matter for parity because the visible counters, filter chips, and note editors update immediately in-place.\n29: \n30: ## Target Architecture\n31: \n32: Plan the HarmonyOS Cangjie target around business domains instead of mirroring every Compose file one-for-one:\n33: \n34: - `entry/src/main/cangjie/ohos_app_cangjie_entry/app/` for app shell, startup, and route composition.\n35: - `entry/src/main/cangjie/ohos_app_cangjie_entry/domain/` for immutable models and route-safe view data.\n36: - `entry/src/main/cangjie/ohos_app_cangjie_entry/data/` for fixture loading, session repository logic, and preference-backed login state.\n37: - `entry/src/main/cangjie/ohos_app_cangjie_entry/features/onboarding|login|home|history|detail|cart|profile/` for feature stores and page composition.\n38: - `entry/src/main/cangjie/ohos_app_cangjie_entry/common/` for reusable widgets, formatting helpers, and resource adapters.\n39: - `entry/src/main/resources/base/` plus `AppScope/resources/` for strings, colors, images, app icon, startup visuals, and page profile wiring.\n40: \n41: Thin ability/page shell files may compose feature stores, but they should not absorb repository or preference logic.\n42: \n43: ## Phase Plan\n44: \n45: ### Phase 1: `phase-01-project-skeleton-resources`\n46: \n47: - Goal: bootstrap the HarmonyOS entry module, resource tree, startup wiring, and domain/data skeleton.\n48: - Key outputs:\n49:   - Target entry module from the mapcir skeleton.\n50:   - AppScope and entry metadata files.\n51:   - Core domain models.\n52:   - Resource catalog for strings, colors, and media copied/adapted from source drawables and mipmaps.\n53:   - Placeholder service boundaries for fixture content and persisted login state.\n54: - Gate:\n55:   - `C:\\Users\\Sieger\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\python.exe D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\scripts\\shared\\reports\\build_hap_report.py --workspace-root D:\\workspace\\Foodike --target-project D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony --phase phase-01-project-skeleton-resources`\n56: - Review focus:\n57:   - Entry package normalization to `ohos_app_cangjie_entry`.\n58:   - App icon, startup resources, and base strings exist.\n59:   - No broad shell file owns all business logic.\n60: \n61: ### Phase 2: `phase-02-startup-navigation-session`\n62: \n63: - Goal: implement startup route resolution, persisted login state, and the shared application shell.\n64: - Key outputs:\n65:   - Preference-backed login state service.\n66:   - Startup/session store that resolves first route before page composition.\n67:   - App navigation host with onboarding, login, home, history, cart, profile, and detail routes.\n68:   - Shared bottom-bar and floating cart-button shell behavior, including route and scroll gating.\n69: - Gate:\n70:   - `C:\\Users\\Sieger\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\python.exe D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\scripts\\shared\\reports\\build_hap_report.py --workspace-root D:\\workspace\\Foodike --target-project D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony --phase phase-02-startup-navigation-session`\n71: - Review focus:\n72:   - Startup does not flash the wrong initial page.\n73:   - Login/logout mutations immediately change visible navigation behavior.\n74:   - Route ownership remains separate from data services.\n75: \n76: ### Phase 3: `phase-03-onboarding-login-profile`\n77: \n78: - Goal: land the onboarding, login, and profile user flows with persisted session semantics.\n79: - Key outputs:\n80:   - Three-page onboarding sequence with progress indicators and next/final navigation behavior.\n81:   - Login form state, hard-coded credential validation, snackbar error path, and successful login transition to home.\n82:   - Profile page sections, static profile visuals, and logout mutation that clears the shell stack to onboarding.\n83: - Gate:\n84:   - `C:\\Users\\Sieger\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\python.exe D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\scripts\\shared\\reports\\build_hap_report.py --workspace-root D:\\workspace\\Foodike --target-project D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony --phase phase-03-onboarding-login-profile`\n85: - Review focus:\n86:   - Login failure messaging remains immediate and non-blocking.\n87:   - Persisted login state survives app restart semantics.\n88:   - Placeholder social/signup/profile edit actions are visibly retained as non-implemented affordances, not silently removed.\n89: \n90: ### Phase 4: `phase-04-home-history-discovery`\n91: \n92: - Goal: implement fixture-backed discovery screens and restaurant selection flow.\n93: - Key outputs:\n94:   - Fixture content repository and session repository.\n95:   - Home screen sections for top bar, greeting, search bar, ads, recommended cards, favourites, filters, and restaurant list.\n96:   - History page with tab state and favourite restaurant selection flow.\n97:   - Shared selection command that stores the current restaurant before detail navigation.\n98: - Gate:\n99:   - `C:\\Users\\Sieger\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\python.exe D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\scripts\\shared\\reports\\build_hap_report.py --workspace-root D:\\workspace\\Foodike --target-project D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony --phase phase-04-home-history-discovery`\n100: - Review focus:\n101:   - Favourite sections render only when non-empty.\n102:   - Filter chips and search bar preserve immediate local-state updates.\n103:   - Selection and navigation happen in the same order as the source: save restaurant first, then navigate.\n104: \n105: ### Phase 5: `phase-05-detail-cart-state-mutations`\n106: \n107: - Goal: implement restaurant detail, menu section expansion, local quantity controls, and cart rendering semantics.\n108: - Key outputs:\n109:   - Detail store fed by session-selected restaurant and repository snapshots.\n110:   - Recommended/non-veg/veg section grouping with expandable headers and icon rotation semantics.\n111:   - Local liked toggle state.\n112:   - Menu item quantity controls with immediate UI updates.\n113:   - Floating cart button visibility driven by non-zero summed item counts.\n114:   - Cart page sections for selected items, note editor, coupon input shell, delivery card, and bill section.\n115: - Gate:\n116:   - `C:\\Users\\Sieger\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\python.exe D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\scripts\\shared\\reports\\build_hap_report.py --workspace-root D:\\workspace\\Foodike --target-project D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony --phase phase-05-detail-cart-state-mutations`\n117: - Review focus:\n118:   - Immediate visible updates for expansion toggles, add/subtract controls, and note text.\n119:   - Detail-to-cart routing is preserved.\n120:   - Any simplification between local detail quantity state and repository cart state must be documented explicitly in coverage records if retained.\n121: \n122: ### Phase 6: `phase-06-polish-tests-verification`\n123: \n124: - Goal: close resource gaps, add focused tests, and verify high-risk behavior before row-level coverage backfill.\n125: - Key outputs:\n126:   - Target tests for session persistence, startup route resolution, login validation, route selection commands, and pure state reducers/helpers.\n127:   - Resource completeness check for missing strings and media references.\n128:   - Final build-gate evidence and any explicit deferred items recorded with risk.\n129: - Gate:\n130:   - `C:\\Users\\Sieger\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\python.exe D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\scripts\\shared\\reports\\build_hap_report.py --workspace-root D:\\workspace\\Foodike --target-project D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony --phase phase-06-polish-tests-verification`\n131: - Review focus:\n132:   - No unresolved string/media references.\n133:   - Target tests verify behavior that source tests did not cover.\n134:   - Coverage and capability backfill can proceed narrowly from the completed plan.\n135: \n136: ## Test Strategy\n137: \n138: - Source tests are only boilerplate examples and do not cover app behavior.\n139: - Add target-side tests for:\n140:   - login preference persistence and startup destination resolution\n141:   - login credential validation and snackbar error emission\n142:   - restaurant-selection command behavior\n143:   - detail section expansion and floating-cart visibility state\n144:   - filter helper mapping and any extracted formatting helpers\n145: - Prefer `cjpm test` where the target template supports it. If the HarmonyOS template blocks runnable tests, keep logic in small pure modules and record the exact harness limitation before relying on compile-only evidence.\n146: \n147: ## Resource Plan\n148: \n149: - Migrate all 52 source strings into HarmonyOS string resources before feature-complete review.\n150: - Copy and adapt all referenced bitmap/vector assets used by onboarding, login, cards, icons, splash, and app icon.\n151: - Convert Android theme values into HarmonyOS startup colors and page token resources.\n152: - Preserve content descriptions and user-facing labels where they are visible or accessibility-relevant.\n153: \n154: ## Platform Capability Decisions For Planning\n155: \n156: - Persisted preferences/login state: required and should map to a direct HarmonyOS preference/storage API.\n157: - Startup splash behavior: required, but exact API may be platform-replaced with HarmonyOS startup-page behavior if direct splash parity differs.\n158: - Localization resources: required and should map to HarmonyOS resource bundles.\n159: - Runtime permissions: currently not source-backed as a real user flow; keep as a reviewed capability row but do not plan first-phase implementation work for it.\n160: - Media library, SAF/file access, notifications/widgets: currently not source-backed; keep these out of active implementation scope unless later source inspection contradicts the walkthrough.\n161: \n162: ## Missing Inputs\n163: \n164: - `translation-inputs/plan-validation-report.md` and `.json` are missing.\n165: - `translation-inputs/phase-task-checklist.md` and `.json` are missing.\n166: - `translation-inputs/phase-capability-checklist.md` and `.json` are missing.\n167: - `translation-inputs/test-build-reports/` is missing.\n168: - Several Kotlin sidecar summaries listed in `task-planning.md` are missing, but the primary Kotlin analysis, locations, Android analysis, walkthrough, and source inspection were sufficient for planning.\n169: - `translation-inputs/mapcir/skeleton-hybrid/` is missing; the plain skeleton is present and sufficient for bootstrap planning.\n170: \n171: ## Deferred Risks\n172: \n173: - The source cart/detail mutation model is inconsistent: quantity changes are local to `MenuItemCard`, while cart data comes from a separate in-memory repository snapshot. Target implementation should preserve visible behavior first, but the final parity record may require an `implemented-simplified` note unless this mismatch is harmonized carefully.\n174: - Source search and chip filters currently keep local UI state without repository filtering logic. Removing them would be a regression, but over-implementing new filtering semantics would also diverge from source behavior.\n175: - Static analysis still tags many files with permissions/file/media concerns that are not source-backed. Coverage and platform records should be updated later with source-evidence notes to avoid false implementation pressure.\n176: - The target project is currently empty; phase 1 must establish a valid entry module before any row-level planned-phase backfill can safely validate target endpoints.\n\n(End of file - total 176 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Foodike HarmonyOS Cangjie Migration Plan\n\n## Scope\n\n- Source project: `D:\\Kotlin2Cangjie\\Foodike`\n- Target project: `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony`\n- Session type: planning only\n- Source app shape: single-module Jetpack Compose app with splash-gated startup, Compose navigation, static fixture-backed content, and DataStore-backed login persistence.\n\n## Confirmed Source Behavior\n\n- Startup uses `SplashViewModel` plus Android splash screen keep-on-screen behavior to resolve the first route before showing the app shell.\n- Initial route is `onboarding` when login state is false and `home` when login state is true.\n- Navigation shell owns the nav controller, a shared list scroll state, a floating cart button, and conditional bottom-bar visibility.\n- Onboarding is a three-page pager with next-step progression and final navigation to login.\n- Login stores only a boolean logged-in flag. Valid credentials are hard-coded to `abcxyz@gmail.com` and `abcdef`; invalid login emits a snackbar.\n- Home loads ads, recommended food cards, restaurant lists, and favourites from repositories. Selecting a restaurant stores the active restaurant in session state before navigating to detail.\n- History reads liked restaurants from the same session repository and also stores the selected restaurant before navigating to detail.\n- Restaurant detail reads the selected restaurant, derives recommended/non-veg/veg menu sections, toggles section expansion and local liked state, and shows the floating cart button only when the summed local item count is non-zero.\n- Cart currently reads repository cart snapshots but keeps bill totals, delivery restaurant, item-note editor, and quantity buttons mostly as local UI behavior with no persistent mutation wiring.","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"plan.md","time":{"start":1782387528242,"end":1782387528252}},"id":"prt_efe93522f0023QnQZCm0547PoM","sessionID":"ses_1016ce029ffemCaBB5i2jTaXCt","messageID":"msg_efe933ccf001HylW623iKQze4Y"}}
